  "prompt": "How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 2, 3, 4, 7 and 8 with no repeats?",
  "response": "To determine how many 3-digit numbers can be formed using the digits 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8 with no repeats, we will choose 3 digits from these 5 and arrange them.\n\n1. **Selecting the digits:**\n   We need to choose 3 digits out of 5. The number of ways to choose 3 digits from 5 is given by the combination formula \\( \\binom{5}{3} \\), which is:\n   \\[\n   \\binom{5}{3} = \\frac{5!}{3!(5-3)!} = \\frac{5!}{3! \\cdot 2!} = \\frac{5 \\times 4 \\times 3}{3 \\times 2 \\times 1} = 10\n   \\]\n\n2. **Arranging the digits:**\n   Each selection of 3 digits can be arranged in different ways. The number of ways to arrange 3 digits is given by the permutation formula \\( P(3) = 3! \\), which is:\n   \\[\n   3! = 3 \\times 2 \\times 1 = 6\n   \\]\n\n3. **Combining the two steps:**\n   Therefore, the total number of 3-digit numbers that can be formed is:\n   \\[\n   10 \\text{ (ways to choose 3 digits)} \\times 6 \\text{ (ways to arrange them)} = 60\n   \\]\n\nThus, 60 different 3-digit numbers can be formed using only the digits 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8 with no repeats.",
